# Scrape

You scrape a single web page via Firecrawl's `/v2/scrape` endpoint and return clean markdown. Firecrawl strips nav/header/footer/ads at the HTML level, blocks cookie banners, and converts the main content to markdown.

If `$ARGUMENTS` is provided, treat it as the URL (or a URL with extra context) and run the scrape immediately. Otherwise ask the user for the URL.

## Tool

```bash
${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}/scripts/scrape.py "<url>" [flags]
```

Output: a small header (`# Title`, `URL:`, `Status:`), then `---`, then the page markdown. With `--include-links`, an extra `## Links` section.

## Flags — when to use which

- **(none)** — the default. Just `<url>`. Markdown only, cached up to 2 days, auto proxy.
- **`--fresh`** — bypass the 2-day cache. Use when the user says "latest", "current", "today's", "just published", or you have any reason to think the page changed recently.
- **`--wait-for 5000`** — extra 5s delay before grabbing content. Use as a **retry** when the first attempt comes back empty or just navigation (likely a JS-rendered SPA). Don't add it preemptively — it slows every scrape.
- **`--mobile`** — emulate a mobile device. Use only when the user explicitly wants the mobile view or the page is known to be mobile-only.
- **`--proxy enhanced`** — use enhanced anti-bot proxies. Use as a **retry** when the first attempt returned a 403 or anti-bot block. Costs more (up to 5 credits) — don't use preemptively.
- **`--include-links`** — also list extracted links. Use when the user wants to follow up by scraping linked pages, or asks for "links on the page".

## Workflow

1. **Scrape** — call the script with just the URL.
2. **Inspect** — if the markdown is empty or contains only navigation/menu text, retry once with `--wait-for 5000`. If the call returned a 403-style error, retry with `--proxy enhanced`. Otherwise proceed.
3. **Present** — paste the markdown verbatim by default. Keep the header block (title/URL/status) so the user can see what was scraped. Only summarize if the user asked for a summary.

## Output discipline

- **Default to verbatim.** The user invoked `/scrape` because they want the content. Don't paraphrase, summarize, or trim unless asked.
- **Preserve the header block** (title, URL, status) — it's the audit trail.
- **Markdown is large.** A typical page is 5–50 KB; long-form articles can hit several hundred KB. If the page is huge and the user's intent looks like "I want to know X about this page", you may summarize the answer to X and offer the full markdown on request.
- **Never fabricate URLs or content.** The script's output is the source of truth.

## Common mistakes

- Adding `--wait-for` or `--proxy enhanced` preemptively. Both slow / cost more — only use them as targeted retries.
- Summarizing when the user asked for the page content. Default verbatim, summarize on request.
- Calling scrape on plain files (`.md`, `.txt`, `.json`, OpenAPI specs). Use `curl -s URL` instead — no extraction needed and no Firecrawl credit burned.
- Treating a near-empty markdown as success. Inspect; retry with `--wait-for 5000` once before reporting.

## Setup

The script reads `FIRECRAWL_API_KEY` from the environment. Get a key at
https://firecrawl.dev and export it before invoking the skill.
